    1	# Inversion Search: Results
    2	
    3	**Date:** 2026-04-04 (Session context)
    4	**Script:** inversion_search.py
    5	
    6	## What Was Tested
    7	Exact formula for the nth prime via inverting the Riemann R function. Six parts: (1) li^{-1}(n) as approximation, (2) correction functions g(n), (3) R^{-1}(n) inversion, (4-5) fixed-point iteration p_{k+1} = R^{-1}(n + sum_rho R(p_k^rho)), (6) analysis of the zero-sum correction.
    8	
    9	## Key Findings
    10	- li^{-1}(n) overestimates systematically; error grows as sqrt(p(n))*ln(p(n)) consistent with RH
    11	- R^{-1}(n) is much better than li^{-1}(n) but still not always roundable to correct prime
    12	- Fixed-point iteration converges with 500 zeta zeros: exact by rounding at k=0 or k=1 for most tested n up to 10000
    13	- The correction sum_rho R(x^rho) is oscillatory, grows as ~sqrt(x)/ln(x), cannot be replaced by elementary function
    14	- The iteration is a direct consequence of inverting pi(x) = R(x) - sum_rho R(x^rho) -- not a new discovery per se
    15	- Computing the zero sum requires O(sqrt(x)) zeta zeros for exact results -- same complexity barrier
    16	
    17	## Verdict
    18	**CLOSED**
    19	**Failure Mode:** I (Information Loss) -- the correction requires O(sqrt(x)) zeta zeros, encoding incompressible oscillatory information
    20	
    21	## One-Line Summary
    22	R^{-1} inversion with fixed-point iteration works but requires O(sqrt(x)) zeta zeros for exactness -- no polylog shortcut.
    23	
