    Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding TC0 circuit complexity lower bounds:
    
    ## Key Findings
    
    A single G(k) gate requires exponential-size TC0 circuits for k = Ω(nε), which represents progress on understanding TC0 lower bounds through generalized circuit classes.
    
    Polynomial-method lower bounds for AC0[p] lift to GC0[p] with no loss in parameters, and Majority requires depth-d GC0[p] circuits of size 2Ω(n1/2(d−1)), matching the state-of-the-art lower bounds for AC0[p].
    
    ## Important Open Problems
    
    Whether TC0 ⊊ NC1 remains an open problem in circuit complexity. Additionally, whether TC0 ⊆ NC1 is a strict inclusion is "one of the main open problems in circuit complexity", and it is even open whether TC0 ⊆ P/poly is a strict inclusion.
    
    The 2026 arXiv results appear to focus on TC0 in relation to other circuit classes and generalized gate functions, rather than establishing new direct lower bounds for TC0 itself, which remains a challenging open problem in circuit complexity theory.
    
    
