    1	# Prime Research: Computing p(n) Exactly Without Bruteforcing
    2	
    3	## Goal
    4	Find an O(polylog) algorithm to compute the nth prime p(n) exactly.
    5	Target: p(10^100) in <1 second, 100% accurate.
    6	
    7	## Status (April 2026)
    8	- **525+ approaches tested** across 37 sessions, 197+ sub-agents
    9	- **All known paths closed** but no proof that polylog is impossible
    10	- **Problem is genuinely open** -- no unconditional lower bound beyond Omega(log x)
    11	- **Proving impossibility faces Natural Proofs barrier** -- as hard as P != NP (S23)
    12	- **pi(x) mod 2 is random-like in 20+ structural measures** (S35)
    13	- Best exact: `algorithms/v10_c_accelerated.py` -- O(p(n)^{2/3}), p(10^9) in 0.175s
    14	- Best approximate: R^{-1}(n) -- O(polylog), ~50% digits correct
    15	- **TECH DEBT RESOLVED (S37):** All 351 experiment scripts now have _results.md companions.
